      h1 Genesis, age, evolution
      p According to many Romanian and foreign scientists, the Danube Delta was formed in a bay of the Black Sea starting in Upper Pleistocene. At this stage a coastal belt was sketched, called the "initial belt", which was considered to have started in the center, in 12,000 BC and continued until 7,500 BC. The formation of this initial belt, which corresponds to the central axis of the Jibrieni, Letea, Caraorman and Crasnicol banks alignment, closed the bay, turning it into a lagoon. Delta has evolved in close connection with the three arms – St. Gheorghe, Sulina and Chilia. The three arms have different ages, the oldest being St. Gheorghe, in the South and the youngest, in the North, named Chilia.
